description:
secretx-core/src/lib.rs:56: SecretValue::new(Vec<u8>) is the only constructor. A backend that already has a Zeroizing<Vec<u8>> (e.g. one that obtained it from another zeroize-aware crate) must call .to_vec() on it first — which produces a non-Zeroizing copy of the bytes — to feed it to ::new().

This is the wrong direction: the goal is to NEVER have non-Zeroizing copies of secret bytes. A construction path from Zeroizing<Vec<u8>> to SecretValue is needed.

Fix:
    impl From<Zeroizing<Vec<u8>>> for SecretValue {
        fn from(z: Zeroizing<Vec<u8>>) -> Self { SecretValue(z) }
    }
Or equivalently a SecretValue::from_zeroizing constructor. Adding both is fine — From for generic interop, named constructor for discoverability.

Same situation for any String-shaped secret: either accept Zeroizing<String> via From, or accept &str + a 'this is a secret string' marker that builds the Zeroizing<Vec<u8>> internally.
